article.headline: Melvin nets double-double, Beard nearly so
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four players scored in double figures for the
Washington Mystics, whose defense stymied the Connecticut Sun for a
67-59 victory Saturday in game one of their opening-round WNBA
Eastern Conference playoff series.

Chasity Melvin had 17 points and 11 rebounds to lead the
Mystics, who have won six of their last seven. Rookie Alana Beard
finished with 13 points, eight rebounds and five assists. Stacey
Dales-Schuman and Aiysha Smith added 10 points apiece.

"It's just us playing together," Melvin said. "It's not a
one-man show. We have to play together and we understand that."

The Mystics went 8-4 in the regular season without leading
scorer and rebounder Chamique Holdsclaw, who missed 12 of their
last 13 games and the playoffs because of an undisclosed medical
issue.

"It is unbelievable how we came together as a team," Beard
said. "We are like sisters now. It wasn't like that at the
beginning. Now we are out there fighting for each other."

Lindsay Whalen scored 16 points to lead the Sun, who shot 36
percent, including 3-for-14 from 3-point range. Former Mystic Asjha
Jones scored 14 points and Taj McWilliams-Franklin added 11 points
and nine rebounds.

The best-of-three series resumes Monday night at Connecticut.

"It's hard to win a playoff game when you shoot 35 percent,"
Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "We had three starters combine for
4-for-23. That's probably not going to win too many."

Nykesha Sales matched her season low with four points, nine
below her average. Sales went 1-for-9, Wendy Palmer shot 1-for-6
and Katie Douglas was 2-for-8.

"We did struggle at times," Whalen said. "We shot in the
thirties and they got to some loose balls. They came with a good
defensive scheme and made us take tough shots."

Smith's 3-pointer gave Washington a 61-50 lead with 4:14 left.

Whalen hit a jumper and a 3-pointer to pull the Sun to 61-55
with 3:23 left but that was as close as Connecticut would get.

"We had hands in their faces to contest shots," Mystics coach
Michael Adams said. "When we do that we give ourselves a chance to
win."

Smith and Melvin both made back-to-back buckets as the Mystics
went on an 8-0 run for a 54-42 lead with 7:02 left.

"The chemistry on our team is at its peak," Dales-Schuman
said. "A lot of people underestimated us as a team and forgot how
good we can be."

Jones came off the bench to score 10 of Connecticut's final 15
points of the first half as the Sun cut a 12-point deficit to 30-27
at halftime. She scored six straight points in the Sun's 8-0 run to
pull to 24-20.

The Mystics shot 7-for-11 from the field during an 18-5 run to
take a 24-12 lead on Melvin's two free throws with 7:14 remaining
in the first half.

The Sun, who are 4-14 when they score less than 70 points, shot
5-for-16 in the opening 10 minutes.
